## 7. Edge Cases and Design Decisions

### Relation fields (`kind === 'object'`)

Relation fields are excluded from all four input types (`CreateInput`, `UpdateInput`, `WhereUniqueInput`) and from the primary model interface. The generated interface only represents the scalar columns a REST API would typically transport. If the API returns nested objects, users can extend the generated interface manually.

The primary model interface (`User`) also excludes relation fields because a GET /users endpoint typically only returns scalar columns; the spec example shows this pattern.

### Auto-generated IDs (`isId: true && hasDefaultValue: true`)

Excluded from `CreateInput` (the server assigns the value). Included in `WhereUniqueInput` as optional (for lookups). Excluded from `UpdateInput` (IDs are not updateable via PATCH).

### Non-auto IDs (`isId: true && hasDefaultValue: false`)

Included in `CreateInput` as required (the client must provide it — e.g., a UUID the client generates). Excluded from `UpdateInput`. Included in `WhereUniqueInput`.

### `@updatedAt` fields (`isUpdatedAt: true`)

Excluded from both `CreateInput` and `UpdateInput`. The server manages this automatically. The field is included in the primary model interface since GET responses include it.

### Nullable list fields (`isRequired: false && isList: true`)

`fieldToTsType` returns `string[] | null`. The array notation is applied before nullability so this is correct.

### Enum fields in `WhereUniqueInput`

An enum field would only appear in `WhereUniqueInput` if it also has `isUnique: true` or `isId: true`. In that case it gets the enum type name as its TS type (e.g., `status?: PostStatus`). This is correct per the scalar-map logic: `kind === 'enum'` returns `field.type` (the enum name).

### Unsupported fields

`kind === 'unsupported'` maps to `unknown` in the model interface and input types. The field is not excluded, preserving the field in the interface while communicating to users that the type is opaque.

### Empty models

If a model has no fields, the interfaces will be `{}` which is valid TypeScript.

### Model name pluralization

The simple `lowerFirst(name) + 's'` heuristic works for the majority of English nouns (`User` → `users`, `Post` → `posts`, `Comment` → `comments`). It breaks for irregular plurals (`Category` → `categorys` instead of `categories`). This is a known limitation documented in the generated code. Adding `pluralize` as a dependency later is straightforward.

